<TEXT>
fire swept through a soviet passenger ship 
in this western japanese port early wednesday killing 10 people 
and injuring 35 the fire bureau said many of those aboard were 
soviet students and workers 
ten bodies were recovered from the docked 4870ton priamurye 
most from a still smoldering section of a passenger cabin the last 
about 10 hours after the blaze broke out said toshio yabuno of the 
osaka city fire bureau 
he said the victims identities and nationalities were not known 
white smoke billowed from the ship as fire squads pumped water 
into the lower decks firefighters wearing oxygen masks plunged 
through the smoke to rescue people trapped aboard the ship 
thirtyfive people were injured in the predawn blaze most from 
smoke inhalation said yabuno he said 28 of the injured were taken 
to hospitals and the seven others were treated at the port area for 
minor burns or bruises 
the cause of the fire was not known said yoshiaki kataoka of 
the maritime safety agencys regional headquarters in okobe the 
agency was informed of the blaze about 150 am 1250 pm edt 
tuesday he said 
kataoka said many of the passengers were soviet students and 
workers visiting japan on a tour organized by the communist youth 
league 
the ship was carrying 295 passengers and 129 crew members when 
it arrived tuesday at osaka 255 miles west of tokyo kataoka said 
firefighters temporarily stopped battling the blaze at one point 
because water pumped into the lower decks had caused the ship to 
list the extra water was removed 
police cordoned off the area and ambulences sped to the dock 
the priamurye left vladivostok on may 7 and made stops at otaru 
on japans northern island of hokkaido and in tokyo on thursday 
it was to have left for hiroshima the official said 
soviet consular officials took most passengers to a junior high 
school gymnasium 
the worst ship disaster in recent years involving a soviet 
cruise vessel occurred on aug 31 1986 when the admiral nakhimov 
sank in the black sea after colliding with the freighter pyotr 
vasyev with the loss of 398 lives 
both captains were sentenced to 15year prison terms 
on feb 16 1986 the 20000ton soviet cruise liner mikhail 
lermonov slammed into rocks off new zealand and sank but although 
the liner was carrying more than 700 passengers and crew there was 
only one fatality a soviet crew member 
</TEXT>
