<TEXT>
scientists are testing a new way to gauge the 
invisible water vapor in the air a measurement that could clear up 
some of the problems in predicting sudden storms 
their new device measures the weak microwaves given off by water 
vapor allowing them to calculate the amount of water in the air 
above national oceanic and atmospheric administration researchers 
in boulder colo are using a radiometer to measure the radiation 
ed westwater a supervisory physicist at the noaa wave 
propagation laboratory said the readings are particularly helpful 
in detecting sudden changes in moisture such as when a front 
passes through an area 
the radiometer can measure the water vapor every two minutes 
and tests at stapleton airport in denver have found occasions when 
the amount rose or fell as much as four times in a half hour 
westwater said 
knowing about a change like that can help a meteorologist trying 
to predict whether rain or snow will occur and when it could be a 
major factor in issuing a warning of a sudden storm said the 
researcher 
westwater said atmospheric water vapor typically has been 
measured using balloons and satellites 
the balloons give the most detail radioing back the amount of 
water vapor at different levels above the earth but they are only 
launched every 12 hours 
satellites can give continuous readings by measuring the 
infrared radiation given off by water vapor but they cant see 
through clouds so their readings often are unavailable westwater 
said 
while four of the microwave meters are undergoing tests no 
schedule for putting them into active operation has been set money 
is among the problems 
the machines cost nearly 100000 each but companies are 
working on instruments which could sell for as little as 25000 
westwater said 
</TEXT>
