<TEXT>
the most severe test firing yet of a 
redesigned space shuttle booster rocket appears to have been a 
success but nasa officials say they wont be certain until the 
booster is disassembled 
everything weve seen in the whole program is looking very 
positive john mccarty head of the marshall space flight 
centers propulsion lab said after tuesdays test it gives us a 
lot of confidence 
the booster was redesigned after the space shuttle challenger 
exploded shortly after liftoff jan 28 1986 when exhaust burned 
through a joint in one of the segmented boosters the test which 
included intentionally flawed booster joints had been postponed 
from last week 
jim thomas technical assistant in the marshall motor project 
office said the absence of bubbles in a bead of grease placed 
outside the redesigned joints indicated they did not leak during 
the test 
the old joint design probably would have failed such a test 
mccarty said 
the test was the fourth of 10 being conducted on the redesigned 
rocket in preparation for augusts shuttle launching it was the 
final test firing of a shortened version of the redesigned booster 
shuttle managers said the firing of the 52footlong booster at 
marshall was the most severe test yet of the redesigned joints 
two joints the casetonozzle joint and the igniter joints 
were intentially flawed through as many as three layers of 
insulation and seals including the last seal intended to keep hot 
exhaust gas from escaping 
it shows the redesigned joints will seal even though we had 
some pretty severe flaws said thomas 
the firing which lasted less than a second generated 960 
pounds of pressure and a temperature of more than 5000 degrees 
fahrenheit inside the case the nozzle end of the stack was plugged 
for two minutes to allow gas to reach the joints 
thomas said the test was unprecedented in the solid rocket 
motor industry but he added the national aeronautics and space 
administration probably wont testfire a fulllength booster the 
same way 
the abbreviated booster tests show the design is tolerant to 
flaws of this type thomas said 
the fifth test of the redesigned booster is planned for the last 
week of july officials said the tests began in november 
</TEXT>
