sir brandon rhys williams a legislator with the 
governing conservative party in the house of commons died today 
he was 60 
williams who has represented the west london constituency of 
kensington for 20 years died at westminster hospital the hospital 
said 
his secretary primrose palmer said williams died of pneumonia 
while undergoing treatment for leukemia he was hospitalized in 
early april she said 
williams death will force the first special election for the 
house of commons since prime minister margaret thatcher won a third 
term last summer 
he won 47 percent of the kensington vote in the june 11 general 
election in which the conservatives won a 102seat majority in the 
650member house of commons 
williams inherited from his family the title of baronet he 
served as a lieutenant in the welsh guards from 1946 to 1948 and 
unsuccessfully contested labor seats in south wales two times in 
the late 1950s and 1960s 
he was a member of the european parliament representing 
southeast london between 1973 and 1984 
williams is survived by his wife caroline one son and two 
daughters 
