the soviet ambassador said in a letter published 
wednesday that moscow has lost radio contact with one of its 
nuclearpowered reconnaissance satellites 
british legislator irvine patnick said he wrote to the 
ambassador leonid zamyatin after hearing news reports that cosmos 
1900 which tracks us naval movements could crash in britain and 
bring significant amounts of nuclear radiation with it 
he said zamyatin apparently wanted to allay any fears when he 
wrote that the satellite continues its oriented flight and all 
major systems operate according to program 
as for radiation zamyatin wrote that cosmos 1900 is equipped 
with the systems providing radiological security on the termination 
of the flight 
concern over the satellites nuclear payload has been mounting 
since the official soviet news agency tass reported may 11 that it 
might fall to earth in august or september 
us experts have claimed that its radioactive components would 
probably not burn up on reentering the atmosphere as tass had 
implied 
the precise effect of the satellites reentry remain a topic 
for debate 
don kerr an expert on military and space technology at the 
international institute for strategic studies in london said the 
satellites small nuclear reactor would absolutely not survive 
reentry intact but some radiation would inevitably cling to the 
satellites parts 
two soviet satellites have fallen to earth before in northern 
canada in 1978 and in the indian ocean in 1983 the canadian 
satellite gave off small amounts of radiation 
