<TEXT>
us officials are bracing for the possibility 
that kremlin leader mikhail s gorbachev will offer to cut soviet 
troop strength sharply in eastern europe a development he has been 
hinting at for nearly two years 
one possibility said a us official is that gorbachev will 
use the may 29june 2 summit in moscow to suggest that the 
superpowers sit down this fall and discuss cutting their ground 
forces in europe by as much as 25 percent 
another official said gorbachev may wait until after the summit 
to make a dramatic gesture possibly announcing the unilateral 
withdrawal of 50000 to 70000 soviet troops another us official 
said tuesday as many as 100000 red army troops could be pulled 
back all three officials spoke on condition of anonymity 
gorbachev wants to cut conventional forces to free up money 
badly needed for his economic reforms robert legvold director of 
soviet studies at columbia university said in a recent study 
were he able to demobilize a large fraction of the 20 
divisions currently deployed in east germany the gains to his 
modernization program would be sizable legvold said 
condoleeza rice of stanford univerisity told a house committee 
on april 27 that the goal of current soviet strategy including 
their extraordinary flexibility in arms control is to create a 
benign foreign policy environment 
this would allow the soviets to divert resources from direct 
investment in defense and to reap the economic benefits of 
technological cooperation with the advanced capitalist states 
rice said 
western analysts have been predicting such a development since 
june 1986 when gorbachev and warsaw pact allies meeting in 
budapest called for the two sides to reduce their forces along the 
central front by about 500000 soldiers apiece by the early 1990s 
one soviet academic vitaly zhurkin subsequently proposed cuts 
of 1 million men on each side 
zhurkin and other scholars in kremlin think tanks have devoted 
considerable ink to expanding on the doctrine of reasonable 
sufficiency introduced by gorbachev at the 27th communist party 
congress in february 1986 
gorbachev zhurkin and others argue that a nation wastes money 
by building more armaments than it needs to defend itself and that 
the soviet union does not need its current vast tank army to deter 
an attack 
conventional military forces must be lowered to a level of 
reasonable sufficiency that is to a level essential for solving 
only defensive tasks two of zhurkins coleagues andrei kokoshin 
and v larionov wrote in a watershed article published in august 
1987 
to achieve this certain changes will have to occur in the way 
military professionals think legvold quoting them as writing 
soviet military officers including chief of staff marshal 
sergei akhromeyev responded with what they called defensive 
sufficiency a force adequate to deal crushing retaliatory 
blows in other words a massive counterattack against any nato 
aggression 
rice who met last month in moscow with soviet military officers 
and scholars described the internal debate in the kremlin as a 
battle royal 
us government analysts conclude that gorbachev won the debate 
and may be ready to unilaterally cut warsaw pact forces by 50000 
to 100000 troops to win support for a new round of eastwest 
negotiations on conventional forces 
according to the international institute for strategic studies 
in london the soviet union keeps 380000 ground troops at a high 
state of readiness in east germany 80000 in czechoslovakia and 
40000 in poland 
a unilateral soviet withdrawal of that scale would have little 
impact strategically one us official said but the political 
payoff could be immense in western europe where polls show great 
enthusiasm for gorbachevs foreign and domestic policies 
gorbachev appears to have come to the same conclusion reached by 
many in the west including sen sam nunn dga the chairman of 
the senate armed services committee that reducing the soviet 
advantage in conventional forces in europe would help the longterm 
kremlin goal of sharply reducing nuclear arsenals 
the warsaw pact holds a 2to1 edge along the central front 
according to pentagon estimates and the iiss in london says the 
soviet bloc has 52200 tanks compared with 22214 in nato 
the rand corp in a study of the conventional balance released 
last january concluded that because of the warsaw pact advantage 
any eastwest agreement on conventional reductions should be on a 
5to1 ratio against the soviet bloc 
earlier talks on reducing conventional forces have been stalled 
since 1973 failing even to produce agreement on the number of 
troops on each side 
reagan administration officials believe a breakthrough may be 
possible because gorbachev seems to have concluded that the warsaw 
pact must make larger cuts than nato to redress its geographic and 
numerical advantages 
</TEXT>
