<TEXT>
closing unneeded military bases is an idea 
whose time has come because of the present drive to cut federal 
spending and reduce the deficit defense secretary frank c 
carlucci said wednesday 
it makes sense to look seriously now at closing bases because 
our military force structure is being reduced and growth in the 
defense budget is being slowed carlucci told a house 
subcommittee 
we must stop spending money to operate bases we do not need 
he said our increasingly scarce resources simply must be applied 
to higher defense priorities so that we do not jeopardize 
americas national security interests 
carlucci was testifying in support of a plan designed to 
surmount the strong reluctance of congress to allow military bases 
to be closed 
the nation has about 3800 military installations and pentagon 
officials estimate that between 2 billion and 5 billion annually 
could be saved if unneeded bases were shut down 
but bases mean jobs and congress has erected such strong 
barriers against base closures that no major installations have 
been closed since 1977 
the current plan calls for creation of a pentagon commission to 
review bases by dec 31 and recommend a list of which can be 
closed carlucci would then have 15 days to accept or reject the 
entire list his decision would be made less than a week before the 
end of president reagans term in office 
the bill offered by rep richard armey rtexas proposes having 
carlucci pick a ninemember commission 
the defense budget bill now pending in the senate calls for a 
15member commission including the nine persons already chosen by 
carlucci and six more who would be selected by carlucci after 
consultation with capitol hill 
the last time the pentagon suggested closing any bases was in 
1985 when a list of 22 was sent to capitol hill but congressional 
outcries halted any action 
using that list as an example carlucci said 6 million could 
have been saved in each of the past two years had the bases been 
shut down 
the list was put together when the pentagon budget was growing 
said carlucci today the opportunity for realignments and 
closures is surely greater than it was three years ago 
we dont expect a larger fighting force he said the air 
force has fewer fighter wings than it was forecasting in 1985 the 
navy has fewer ships than it proposed and the army has fewer combat 
elements a smaller more robust base structure makes far more 
sense now than it has at any time over the past 10 years 
armey said theres been an important twist in the 
baseclosing debate were no longer talking about if we can 
close obsolete bases were talking about how we can close 
obsolete bases 
the commission plan also proposes a onetime waiver that would 
allow the bases to be shut down without going through the complex 
and lengthy environmental reports now required of the pentagon 
carlucci said there was a widespread misconception that base 
closures cause the local community to suffer devastating economic 
effects 
the truth is quite different he said the facts are that 
most communities affected by previous base closures have had strong 
economic recovery 
a pentagon survey of 100 communities where bases had been closed 
show that 94000 defense department civilian jobs were lost but 
they had been replaced by 138000 new civilian jobs he said 
</TEXT>
