<TEXT>
the federal communications commission issued a 
notice wednesday reminding broadcasters that accepting unreported 
payments in exchange for airplay of programming is a crime 
the fcc said it was putting out the reminder in light of the 
recent indictments of four people in california following a 
twoyear investigation of payola practices in the broadcast 
industry 
fcc chairman dennis r patrick said the commission wanted to let 
broadcasters know we will take appropriate action in response 
to any payola allegations 
payola is the unreported payment to or acceptance by employees 
of broadcast stations program producers or program suppliers of 
money or services for airplay of programming 
if matter in a program has been paid for the law requires a 
broadcaster to announce that and to disclose the sponsor 
violations carry criminal penalties of up to one year in prison 
and fines of up to 10000 
in february two independent music promoters a former radio 
executive and a promoters wife were indicted on bribery tax 
evasion and other charges stemming from the payola investigation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

