<TEXT>
us district judge alcee l hastings of miami 
demanded wednesday that a house impeachment panel dismiss 
misconduct allegations brought by fellow judges after his acquittal 
on bribery conspiracy charges five years ago 
i am not guilty but i am not free hastings said in his 
impassioned plea at the start of impeachment hearings by a house 
judiciary subcommittee whose chairman suggested the case against 
floridas first black federal judge might be racially and 
politically motivated 
hastings who was nominated for the federal bench by president 
carter in 1979 was acquitted in 1983 of conspiring to solicit a 
150000 bribe from two convicted racketeers in exchange for a 
promise of lenient sentences 
but a special fivejudge panel of the 11th us circuit court of 
appeals in atlanta concluded after a 3year investigation that 
there was clear and convincing evidence that hastings had 
engaged in a bribery conspiracy and tried to conceal it by lying 
under oath and fabricating evidence at his highly publicized trial 
in miami 
the panels 381page report was endorsed unanimously by the 
27member judicial conference of the united states the chief 
policymaking body of the federal judiciary the conference 
forwarded the report to the house leadership with the conclusion 
that consideration of impeachment may be warranted 
the house judiciary subcommittee on criminal justice after 
conducting its own intensive investigation for more than a year 
opened public hearings wednesday by allowing hastings to deliver a 
sworn statement 
hastings said he was the first federal judge in us history to 
be threatened with impeachment after his acquittal of criminal 
charges 
they found me not guilty of crimes i never committed he 
said 
let me make it very very clear hastings said i have not 
received a bribe i have not obstructed justice and i have not 
betrayed the integrity of the high office that i hold 
his voice rising hastings declared 
i am not guilty but i am not free and i ask you in the name 
of decency in the name of justice in the name of the american 
jury system i ask you in the name of the american way of life 
i beg you i beseech you i implore you hell no i tell you and i 
demand of you that you set me free 
the subcommittee then heard from new york lawyer john doar a 
former assistant us attorney general in the johnson 
administration who reviewed the massive evidence used in the 
investigation he conducted for the appellate panel that charged 
hastings with judicial misconduct 
subcommittee members listened to a series of secretly taped 
conversations and telephone calls in september and october 1981 
involving washington lawyer william a borders and an fbi 
undercover agent posing as racketeer frank romano 
borders was convicted at a separate trial in 1982 on charges to 
arrange the alleged bribe from romano and his brother thomas 
doar said one taped telephone call between borders and hastings 
also played for the subcommittee was a coded conversation that 
concerned the bribery transaction and whether the person they 
thought was frank romano had actually made an initial 25000 down 
payment 
after its factfinding hearings the panel must decide whether 
to recommend impeachment to the full judiciary committee if the 
committee approves articles of impeachment against hastings they 
must be submitted to a house floor vote 
if the house impeaches hastings which would be tantamount to an 
indictment a senate trial would be held a twothirds majority of 
senators would be required to convict hastings of high crimes and 
misdemeanors and force his removal from the federal bench 
hastings lawyers charged in a statement that doar was an 
incompetent witness who was relying on hearsay information they 
also alleged that the appellate panels report includes 
incomplete inaccurate and inadmissible evidence that is 
insufficient to produce a conviction at any senate impeachment 
trial 
the house has never in its 200year history used its 
impeachment powers to inquire into charges gainst a federal judge 
that a jury had rejected after a full trial the lawyers said 
the racial and political overtones of the impeachment inquiry 
were cited by rep john conyers jr dmich the subcommittee 
chairman as soon as he opened the hearing 
conyers said the proceedings were exceedingly difficult and 
trying because hastings had already been acquitted by a trial 
jury and because he is a leader of the black community in florida 
conyers who is black said his subcommittee had taken 
cognizance of racially motivated conduct in this country for many 
many years particularly in the criminal justice system 
he said the federal judiciary had become conservatized and in 
