<TEXT>
a federal appeals court wednesday reinstated 62 
cases against boat operators fined for bringing cubans to the 
united states in the 1980 mariel boatlift 
the cases were among 900 pursued by the immigration and 
naturalization service following the boatlift which brought 
125000 refugees from the cuban port of mariel to florida 
the ins fined the boat owners and operators 1000 for each 
cuban brought to the united states and then filed about 900 
lawsuits against those who failed to pay the fines the lawsuits 
were divided among the judges in the southern disstrict of florida 
us district judge alcee l hastings of miami dismissed all 62 
cases assigned to his court saying the ins had failed to state its 
case correctly the 11th us circuit court of appeals wednesday 
threw out hastings ruling saying the cases had been stated 
sufficiently 
hastings is facing impeachment since fellow judges brought 
unrelated misconduct allegations after his acquittal on bribery 
conspiracy charges five years ago he had hearings wednesday before 
a house judiciary subcommittee in which he demanded dismissal of 
the allegations 
during the lengthy appeals of hastings action on the boatlift 
hastings had rejected attempts by the government to get the cases 
sent back to the ins for reconsideration 
the government asked the appeals court to send all 62 cases to 
the ins but the court sent some cases back to the district court 
and remanded others to the ins the court ruled wednesday the cases 
could not be treated the same because the records before the court 
for some cases were incomplete 
the court also noted that some of the defendants had not been 
served properly with the lawsuits its order gave the government 
120 days to serve those defendants with the proper papers 
</TEXT>
