ethnic minorities will be guaranteed seats in 
parliament under legislation passed wednesday that changes the 
election rules 
goh chok first deputy prime minister said minority groups 
welcomed the change and had said so at public hearings all 
agreed that a multiracial parliament is essential to political 
stability he said 
parliament approved two bills wednesday that amend the 
constitution and revise polling laws to institutionalize 
multiracial politics in this island republic of 26 million people 
more than 76 percent are ethnic chinese malays make up 15 
percent indians 6 percent and the rest are eurasians and others 
the official languages are mandarin english malay and tamil 
prime minister lee kuan yew who first suggested racial 
guarantees in 1982 told the hearings in march that race was a 
constant factor in singapore and chauvinism persisted he said he 
was trying to anticipate problems instead of reacting 
lee said his peoples action party which holds all but one seat 
in parliament had trouble finding candidates in the malay 
community which lags behind other ethnic groups in social 
economic and educational progress 
about 85 percent of singapores people live in governmentbuilt 
apartments and deliberate dispersal of races in the projects has 
prevented concentrations of malay voters who might elect their own 
candidates 
the measures were approved in the 79member parliament by votes 
of 670 with no abstentions and the only opposition member absent 
they provide for group represention constituencies with 
three seats each at least one of which must be filled by a person 
who is malay or from another minority 
lees party has controlled parliament since 1959 the fragmented 
opposition is given little chance of ousting it in the general 
election that must be held by december 1989 
the last parliamentary vote four years ago elected 63 chinese 
nine malays six indians and one eurasian 
