<TEXT>
the winter coat that olga boguslavskys friend 
found at the gum department store during her buying trip to moscow 
cost 730 rubles thats 1170 or almost four months pay for the 
average soviet industrial worker 
for the same money she could have bought enough meat at state 
subsidized prices to last for six years 
consider too the case of the collective farmer who can sell 
the government a kilogram 22 pounds of meat for the established 
wholesale price of 4 rubles and then turn around and use that same 
money to buy back twice as much meat at subsidized retail prices 
economists spearheading soviet leader mikhail s gorbachevs 
economic reforms use examples like these to argue that the 
staterun economys price structure must be revamped 
but soviet consumers long accustomed to lowpriced necessities 
worry openly that higher prices may be the only effects they feel 
