for a twoday fishing expedition 
the fish vigilantes came back 17000 poorer but they got what 
they were looking for videotapes of seven japanese vessels 
allegedly fishing in us waters 
the tapes created an uproar just as hjelle and evans had hoped 
the senate passed a resolution condemning illegal fishing and 
urging a moratorium on doughnut hole fishing the state department 
demanded an explanation from the japanese government and the 
commerce department fined three japanese companies 100000 
soviet and american negotiators last month renewed talks to 
consider closing the doughnut hole to fishing a delicate issue 
involving international law since neither country has jurisdiction 
over the area 
the negotiators have asked other fishing nations to consider a 
moratorium but the response has been weak especially from japan 
a fishhungry nation thats seen traditional worldwide fishing 
grounds shut off by nations declaring 200mile limits 
japan has a long history in the bering sea long before the 
economic zone was claimed by americans said katsuo jodai of the 
japan fisheries association the doughnut hole is high seas 
it does not belong to any country 
so the catandmouse game continues and the mice have a greater 
advantage than ever 
in march yost announced that c130 patrols from kodiak would be 
cut by 35 percent cutter patrols by 55 percent yost he hopes an 
interim funding measure working its way through congress will boost 
patrols this summer but theres no guarantee of funding for next 
year 
the state department meanwhile awaits a reply from the 
japanese on januarys illegal fishing the companies fined by the 
commerce department have yet to pay and their troublesome boats 
after dropping off their catch in hokkaido returned to fish the 
bering sea 
