<DOCNO> AP880518-0316 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations two largest automakers could face 
300 million in penalties because of ruling by a sharply divided 
federal appeals court that upholds revised fuel economy ratings for 
19801984 model cars 
the us circuit court of appeals in washington split 55 along 
ideological lines tuesday leaving intact a 1986 order by a 
threejudge panel of the court the earlier order followed a 
challenge of new environmental protection agency standards by the 
center for auto safety a consumer activist group 
at issue is epas decision in 1985 to raise the fuel economy 
ratings for cars made between 1980 and 1984 to reflect seven 
changes in test procedures ford and gm contended the original 
method had unfairly lowered the ratings 
the higher ratings recalculated by epa lowered penalties against 
ford and gm for falling short of the fueleconomy standards set 
under the environmental policy and conservation act of 1975 
under the law manufacturers are penalized 5 for each tenth of 
a mile a model falls short of the milespergallon standard the 
law also gives manufacturers credits for surpassing the standards 
that can be carried over into subsequent model years 
the threejudge panel had unanimously held that in recalculating 
the ratings epa should also have factored in changes in several 
test procedures that had benefited manufacturers by raising the 
scores 
the full court later vacated the panels ruling and agreed to 
rehear the case 
the automobile manufacturers have never provided an estimate of 
how much the 1986 ruling would cost them but the center for auto 
safety estimates it could result in penalties up to 300 million 
for ford and gm chrysler corp was not affected because its cars 
met the fueleconomy standards for those years 
gm spokesman bill nowack said in a statement that the decision 
is symptomatic of the burdensome problems cafe the fuel economy 
system has represented in recent years which have threatened 
american productivity and jobs but he added that the potential 
impact of the court decision and the expected epa rulemaking are 
yet to be fully determined 
the judges split along liberal and conservative lines over 
whether the center had legal standing to challenge the way the epa 
recalculated the corporate average fuel economy ratings 
chief judge patricia wald who wrote the original 1986 opinion 
tartly accused her conservative colleagues of ignoring legal 
precedent the will of congress and common sense in questioning the 
centers right to bring the case 
conservatives argued that the consumer group lacked legal 
standing because it could not prove that epas decision inflicted 
an economic harm 
the fact that congress has determined that consumers would be 
injured by driving automobiles that use more rather than less fuel 
is of little help in determining whether these petitioners are able 
to establish injuriesinfact sufficiently personal and 
concrete to meet the requirements for legal standing judge james 
l buckley wrote in a dissent he was joined by judges douglas h 
ginsburg stephen williams and kenneth starr 
wald joined by judges abner mikva spottswood robinson ruth b 
ginsburg and harry edwards said the consumers have standing 
because the injury they suffer is a traditional economic one 
higher prices and diminished availability of the goods they seek 
