largest nonindustrial companies found most service companies had 
a rough time in 1987 the october stock market crash brought a 
slump in the brokerage business while savings institutions 
continued to suffer from a rash of bad loans and major commercial 
banks continued to sustain losses on loans to developing countries 
total profits for the 500 biggest service companies dropped 22 
percent in 1987 to 508 billion fortune said by contrast the 
annual fortune 500 survey of the leading industrial companies 
released last month showed a 41 percent jump in profits to 91 
billion 
recent economic statistics such as the us trade deficit for 
march and factory use data for april released on tuesday have 
indicated a resurgence of traditional smokestack industries 
