the federal communications commission on 
wednesday approved construction of a new fiber optic cable under 
the atlantic ocean to link the united states and canada with points 
in europe and the mediterranean region 
the cable known as tat9 is due to be put in service in 1991 
it will have the capacity to transmit 80000 simultaneous 
conversations twice the capacity of another optical fiber cable 
scheduled to go into service between the united states and europe 
this year 
the cable is expected to cost the us carriers and more than 25 
foreign companies participating in the project about 400 million 
the us carriers with a combined 385 percent stake in the 
project include american telephone amp telegraph co mci 
international us sprint trt telecommunications ftcc 
communications comsat communications inc and western union world 
communications atampt owns the largest share at 287 percent 
the cable will link points in the united states canada the 
united kingdom france and spain it also will connect to cable 
systems linking spain and italy and between italy turkey greece 
and israel 
