<TEXT>
general mills said wednesday it is selling 
its talbots womens clothing subsidiary to the japanese company 
jusco co ltd for 325 million and its eddie bauer outdoor 
apparel division to spiegel inc for about 260 million 
talbots and eddie bauer were the only remaining general mills 
subsidiaries not related to food processing and food marketing the 
companys board had been exploring selling the two for several 
months 
the sales will give general mills an aftertax profit exceeding 
200 million in fiscal 1989 said hb atwater jr general mills 
chairman and chief executive officer 
the company plans to use about twothirds of the projected net 
proceeds to repay debt associated with open market purchases of 
over 210 million in general mills common shares in the second half 
of fiscal 1988 and to help finance the companys internal 
investment program atwater said he said most of the remainder is 
targeted for additional stock repurchases during the next several 
months 
general mills has 843 million common shares outstanding 
jusco is one of japans largest retailers the tokyo companys 
diversification efforts included a joint venture company formed 
with general mills in 1982 to develop and operate red lobster 
restaurants in japan 
talbots based in hingham mass sells womens apparel and 
accessories in 126 stores in 26 states its annual sales from the 
stores and its catalogs exceed 340 million about 6 percent of 
general mills total 
spiegel markets womens and mens apparel home furnishings and 
other general merchandise through catalogs 
eddie bauer is a specialty retailer selling mens and womens 
leisure sportswear gifts and outdoor equipment through catalogs 
and 58 retail stores in 14 states and two canadian provinces 
both transactions are expected to be completed within six weeks 
general mills said 
